	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Behind every number is a real person — maybe you, maybe someone you would give anything to bring home. The relapse that arrived after you swore it never would. The relationships strained or broken. The isolation that whispers no one could understand. The exhausting cycle of trying, falling, and trying again. The deep fear that you have run out of chances to be forgiven.</p><p>None of this means you are beyond reach. It means you are human, carrying a weight no one was built to carry alone — and a weight that shame and willpower were never strong enough to lift. There is a Father who sees the real you underneath all of it, who has not given up watching the road, and who has something to say about who you actually are.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `SAMHSA — 2022 National Survey on Drug Use and Health (NSDUH)`, url: `https://www.samhsa.gov/data/report/2022-nsduh-annual-national-report` },
		{ label: `CDC — Drug Overdose Deaths (National Center for Health Statistics)`, url: `https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nvss/vsrr/drug-overdose-data.htm` },
		{ label: `NIH / NIAAA — Alcohol Use Disorder and Recovery`, url: `https://www.niaaa.nih.gov/alcohols-effects-health/alcohol-use-disorder` },
	]}
	aFatherHeading={`A Father for those facing addiction`}
	aFatherBodyHtml={`<p>Here is what shame will never tell you: the answer to addiction is not a louder lecture, a harder white-knuckle, or finally becoming clean enough to deserve love. The answer is a <strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">Father</strong> — the Father of the prodigal, who saw his child while he was still a long way off and ran to meet him.</p><p>You do not have to clean yourself up before you come home. The son in the story rehearsed his apology, but the Father interrupted it with an embrace. There was no probation, no "prove it first," no list of conditions — only a robe, a ring, and a celebration that the one who was lost had been found. That is the heart God reveals toward you.</p><p>So before you are an addict, a relapse, a disappointment, a statistic — you are His. Your heavenly Father wants to be the steady voice underneath the craving and the shame, the one who says: I never stopped watching the road, there is no condemnation here, and there is nothing you have done that could make Me stop running toward you.</p>`}
