	keepReadingHtml={`Start with the <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">whole Bible free online with audio</a>, learn <a href="/the-fathers-heart-bible/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">why the Father's Heart Bible™ exists</a>, or get oriented with our <a href="/guides/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Bible reading guides</a> — including <a href="/guides/how-to-pray/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">how to pray</a> and <a href="/verses/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">verses by topic</a>. Or meet the Father in another season through the rest of the <a href="/bible-for/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">A Father For series</a>.`}
	faqs={[
		{ question: `What are good Bible verses for addiction and recovery?`, answer: `Luke 15:20 (the Father runs to meet the prodigal), Romans 8:1 (no condemnation), 2 Corinthians 5:17 (a new creation), John 8:36 (whom the Son sets free is free indeed), Psalm 34:18 (close to the brokenhearted), Philippians 4:13 (strength for every step), 1 Corinthians 10:13 (a way out of temptation), and Joel 2:25 (He restores the years the locusts have eaten) all speak straight into addiction and recovery. Read and hear them free in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about overcoming addiction?`, answer: `Scripture is honest that you cannot do it on willpower alone — and that you do not have to. 1 Corinthians 10:13 promises God will always provide a way out of temptation, Philippians 4:13 says your strength comes from Him, and John 8:36 says the freedom He gives is real and complete. The Father's Heart Bible™ reveals God as a Father who walks every step of recovery with you — read those passages free, with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Does God still love me after I keep relapsing?`, answer: `Yes — and that is the heart of the whole story. In Luke 15 the prodigal's Father ran to meet him while he was still far off, before a single thing was fixed. Romans 8:1 says there is no condemnation for those who belong to Him. Recovery is rarely a straight line, and your Father is patient with every step. In the Father's Heart Bible™ you meet God as a Father who keeps watching the road for you, no matter how many times you have fallen.` },
		{ question: `Am I beyond forgiveness because of my addiction?`, answer: `No. The shame that says you are beyond forgiveness is not the voice of God. Romans 8:1 says there is no condemnation in Christ, 2 Corinthians 5:17 says you become a whole new creation, and Psalm 34:18 says God is closest to the brokenhearted. In the Father's Heart Bible™ you meet a Father who does not hold your past against you but runs toward you to welcome you home. Read it free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Is there a free Bible with audio for people in recovery?`, answer: `Yes. The Father's Heart Bible™ is free to read and listen to online — no account, no purchase, no app. Open fathersheartbible.com/read on your phone and read or hear any book — ideal for the late-night moment when the craving hits, the ride to a meeting, or the hard day after a relapse when you need His voice close.` },
		{ question: `What makes the Father's Heart Bible™ different for those facing addiction?`, answer: `It is the first English translation to reveal God as Father wherever Scripture reveals Him as Father — so instead of reading one more voice telling you to do better, you meet the One who ran down the road to His child. For someone weighed down by shame and the cycle of addiction, that reframes everything: you come to the Bible as a loved child the Father is running toward, not a case to be judged.` },
		{ question: `How can I start reading the Bible while I am in recovery?`, answer: `Start small and start free. Open fathersheartbible.com/read, pick a short passage, and listen to the audio while you read — Luke 15 (the prodigal), Psalm 34, or Romans 8 are good places to begin. Try a verse a day, especially in the moments the craving or shame is loudest. Our how-to-pray guide and verses-by-topic pages can help you find words for whatever you are facing right now.` },
	]}
	ctaBottomHeading={`You are not beyond His reach`}
